What the Post Is Reporting
The post summarizes a significant result published in Nature (April 2026) from the LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA collaboration.
Main Finding:
Astronomers have now confirmed the existence of the pair-instability mass gap in black holes.
Simple Explanation
When very massive stars die, their fate depends on their mass:
Below a certain mass → They can collapse into black holes.
In a specific mass range → They undergo a pair-instability supernova, which completely destroys the star, leaving no black hole behind.
Above that range → They can again form very massive black holes.
This creates a predicted “forbidden zone” — a range of black hole masses that should be very rare or absent because no standard stellar process can produce them. This is called the pair-instability mass gap.
The new study used the largest collection of black hole merger detections so far and found clear statistical evidence that this gap exists exactly where stellar evolution theory predicted it would.
However, there is one notable exception: the detection of an extremely massive black hole merger (final mass ~225 solar masses), whose progenitor black holes appear to sit near or possibly inside this predicted gap.
